  "prompt": "How long do you have to live on your own (and in poor conditions) to qualify for the Pell Grant? Is the Pell Grant a scholarship for the poor?",
  "response": "The Pell Grant is a need-based federal grant for undergraduate students with significant financial need. It's not directly tied to how long you've lived on your own, but rather to your family's income and financial situation. Key points include:\n\n1. Eligibility is primarily determined by:\n- Family income\n- Family size\n- Cost of attendance at your school\n- Student's dependency status\n\n2. To determine eligibility, you must:\n- Complete the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA)\n- Be an undergraduate student\n- Have not earned a bachelor's, graduate, or professional degree\n- Be a U.S. citizen or eligible non-citizen\n- Have a high school diploma or equivalent\n\n3. It's not a scholarship specifically for those living in poor conditions, but for students with demonstrated financial need.\n\n4. The grant amount varies based on:\n- Expected Family Contribution (EFC)\n- Cost of attendance\n- Enrollment status (full-time or part-time)\n\n5. For the 2023-2024 academic year, the maximum Pell Grant is $7,395.\n\nLiving conditions alone do not automatically qualify you; financial need is the primary factor.",
